         ***Corto don't speak on issues in which you have no knowledge***<BR>Yes, the dictionary definition of "Jihad" is a religious crusade. However when pertaining to the beliefs of the Muslims the term JIHAD, as it has to do with a current events, is a gross political distortion of the period of Qur'anic revelation while Muhammad was in Mecca wherein Jihad was defined as a "nonviolent struggle to spread Islam." If you don't believe me read up on your muslim theology. This distortion of the term JIHAD in today's current events was Al Qaeda's attempt to rally the Muslim-American population to attack from within on the basis of religion. Your criticism has no basis.<BR>President Bush has a right like any other American to maintain the religious beliefs of his choice. <BR>This issue regarding the pledge of allegiance is very simple. No matter how you slice it the Constitution and the Declaration of Independance were based on the concept of freedom of religion. As stated before freedom of; not protectionm from. Regardless of your beliefs they both allude to a "natural God" and "one's creator" no matter your beliefs, they imply theism. Though most of the beliefs of our founding fathers was christianity, these religious implications were left open ended so as not to contradict the concept of freedom of religion. Now how is this relevant. The addition of the words "under god"  to the P.O.A. by Eisenhower were in fact put in to effect under the pretense of Christianity. This is the point that put this topic in to public light. Those were his beliefs. However the use of the word god in the P.O.A. makes no implications to the Christian religion. It simply supports the same non-denominational theistic tone of the Declaration of Independance and the Constitution. </P><P>Point in fact: The Country was founded under the concept of theism. A non specific "god" as part of a pledge of pride and devotion to a country that provides them the option to choose what god means to them, is nothing more then an appreciation for that country's roots.</P><P>If we are going to argue that any connotation to any religious principal is unconstitutional, then the Constitution is Unconstitutional, and where does that leave the American Culture????</P><P></P><P>Edited by - Zyxx_Shadowstealth on 06/27/2002  16:21:52<a href="#top"><img src="icon_go_up.gif" height="15" width="15" border="0" align="right" alt="Go to Top of Page"></a></font></td>
